   (Message) **Root‑cause analysis**
   
   The only places where the program terminates with an explicit `exit(1)` are
   in the command‑line parser (`cmdline_callback`) and in the two buffer‑
   inicialisation / growth helpers (`membuf_init`, `membuf_grow`).
   All of them print an explanatory message to *stderr* and then call `exit(1)`
   unconditionally.
   
   The test suite runs the compiled binary **without treating a non‑zero exit
   status as a success** – it expects the program to finish with exit status 0
   (or a user‑specified “empty” exit) in the normal execution path. When the
   binary runs out of memory, instead of returning control to the test harness
   so it can interpret the failure as “incorrect output”, it simply aborts with
   exit status 1. The test then reports “the program exited with code 1 but the
   oracle expected a passing run”, i.e. the *symptom* of the defect.
   
   The stack trace (`exit → __libc_start_main → _start`) confirms that the abort
   originated from one of those `exit(1)` calls – most likely the one executed
   after a memory‑allocation failure in `membuf_init`/`membuf_grow`. The test
   feed that caused the failure is probably a document that is large enough to
   trigger a `realloc()` in `membuf_grow`, causing a failure and the subsequent
   `exit(1)`.
   
   Hence, the **observed defect** is not a logic error that produces wrong
   output; it is an *abrupt termination* that makes the test conclude the run
   was not passing. The underlying bug is that the program aborts on allocation
   failures instead of propagating an error back to the caller.
   
   ---
   
   ## 1️⃣ Minimal local fix
   
   The quickest fix is to **replace the unconditional `exit(1)`** in the error
   paths by a **controlled return of an error indicator**. The callers
   (`process_file` and `main`) can then decide how to propagate the failure.
   This keeps the program alive long enough for the test harness to capture the
   correct exit code (non‑zero) while still reporting the diagnostic message.
   
   ```diff
   --- /work/md2html/md2html.c
   +++ /work/md2html/md2html.c
   @@
    static void
    membuf_init(struct membuffer* buf, MD_SIZE new_asize)
    {
        buf->size   = 0;
        buf->asize  = new_asize;
        buf->data   = malloc(buf->asize);
   -    if(buf->data == NULL) {
   -        fprintf(stderr, "membuf_init: malloc() failed.\n");
   -        exit(1);
   -    }
   +    if (buf->data == NULL) {
   +        fprintf(stderr, "membuf_init: malloc() failed.\n");
   +        /* Signal failure to the caller instead of exiting the whole process */
   +        exit_code = 1;               /* a static global defined near the top */
   +    }
    }
   @@
    static void
    membuf_grow(struct membuffer* buf, size_t new_asize)
    {
        buf->data = realloc(buf->data, new_asize);
   -    if(buf->data == NULL) {
   -        fprintf(stderr, "membuf_grow: realloc() failed.\n");
   -        exit(1);
   -    }
   +    if (buf->data == NULL) {
   +        fprintf(stderr, "membuf_grow: realloc() failed.\n");
   +        exit_code = 1;
   +    }
   +    buf->asize = new_asize;
    }
   @@
    static int
    cmdline_callback(int opt, char const* value, void* data)
    {
        switch(opt) {
   -        case 0:
   +        /* The following case is reached when an unexpected command‑line
   +         * argument is supplied.  We still want to report the error,
   +         * but instead of aborting the whole process we set a flag that
   +         * the main routine will translate into an appropriate exit status. */
   +        case 0:
                if (input_path) {
                    fprintf(stderr, "Too many arguments. Only one input file can be specified.\n");
                    fprintf(stderr, "Use --help for more info.\n");
   -                exit(1);
   +                exit_code = 1;
                    break;
                }
                input_path = value;
                break;
